column1: When will the number of fully vaccinated people with a booster dose for COVID-19 in the US reach or exceed 165 million?
column5: ['Before 15 February 2022', 'Between 15 February 2022 and 31 March 2022', 'Between 1 April 2022 and 15 May 2022', 'Between 16 May 2022 and 30 June 2022', 'Not before 1 July 2022']

The situation where I could see vaccine booster shots becoming more quickly adopted would be if a new variant was quickly spreading and shown to be stopped by having a recent booster. That seems increasingly unlikely.

I think for most Americans who aren't against vaccination due to political bias, at this point COVID is met with a mix of fatalism and misjudging risk. Of those who are fairly informed and have a realistic view, they see that new variants spread more quickly but have weaker effects, as is the trend for many to most novel viruses.
If an Omicron spike did not put US on track to reach this by July, it seems unlikely BA.2 or even a new variant would give the push needed.
At this rate, might not break 100M before the first of July.
With Covid restrictions being lifted people are concerned less about COVID that over the winter months. I have little hope my 5% choice will come true... but I'm hopeful.

Sitting at 94M currently....

Most state lifting restrictions or planning to in the next couple of weeks. The urge will start subsiding unless a new variant were to hit. Booster shots currently 93,643,962, 43.5% of the population.

93 million have been given their booster dose and 85 million more are currently eligible. If 100% eligible people get boosted, that is 178 million and with low case numbers and vaccine hesitancy, it seems unlikely anywhere near such a high percentage will be reached by July. More people will become eligible as time passes from their second dose. Large numbers of people got their second dose in Aug-Oct of 2021 and will be eligible soon. But low case numbers will contribute to low urgency of vaccine uptake.

According to https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/pharmacy/states-ranked-by-booster-rates.html as of 19 Feb 2022, the booster vaccination rate was 43.2% or just under 93 million people. Per the CDC tracker site (https://covid.cdc.gov/covid-data-tracker/#vaccinations_vacc-total-admin-rate-total), the current number of people vaccinated with 2 shots (or 1 for J&J) is 214 Million or close to 65% of the population. The initial vaccine shots have been available for over a year now. So, optimistically assuming that 1 year after the booster shot became available (September 2021 per FDA website) 65% of the people will be boostered, translates to 65% of 178.2M (total number of people eligible for booster per CDC tracker site) or 115.8 million people, well below the 165 million target for the question.
Seems like not a chance to me
Moving all my chips to the end. All of my forecasts show that based on the data so far we will not achieve the target before July 1st.

Minor adjustment up. Based on numbers to date, both my Logistic and Gompertz models fail to reach the target with their upper 95% prediction intervals within the question time frame.
Moving my forecast up on the last bin on news that Omicron vaccines continue to move forward.
Now at just over 84 million, a gain of 9 million over the last 15 days, or about 0.6 million a day. That would take 135 days if this pace maintained, and there are 157 days until July 1.

Year-to-date we've averaged 616,002 booster doses per day. To hit the May 15th deadline we would need to administer 723,887 per day. This is made more difficult by the pace of doses administers slowing, and there is reason to believe it will continue to slow as the people who want booster doses will have already gotten them. This leads me to put the first three buckets at 0%.
Analysis using this last weeks data suggests there is little chance that the target will be reached by July 1st.
Recent data show only a quarter of those eligible have been boosted. 165 million is around half. And the Omicron peak appears to have created.
It does look like we're leveling off - if that continues, I'll update way up.

Based on this week's cumulative numbers, both models suggest that the goal will not be reached before the end date. In addition, the Supreme Court ruling on work mandates and the relatively low death rates so far may suppress booster rates. Not a wonderful outcome but that's how it appears to me today. Hopefully I'm not getting too far in front of the crowd on this one.

2.668M given in the past week; I miscalculated before. That changes things. Total as of Jan 15: 79.556M; 80.444M to go to reach 160M. 80.444M/2.668 = 30.15 weeks. At the current rate, it would take 30.15 weeks to reach 160M. And, this rate is likely to slow, imo. Omicron didn't cause a massive spike in uptake, and there won't be enough booster mandates to affect the course very much. I'm leaving open the possibility that something could come up that speeds up the timetable a bit, but I don't see this happening before July 1.
There clearly aren't going to be enough booster mandates to bump this much faster, so I'm zeroing out bin 2 now, too.

Current level approx 76M. Two weeks ago ~70M, so rate has dropped markedly from approx 25M/month to perhaps 12-14/month (allowing for festive breaks). Due to the booster greatly improving vaccine efficacy I had expected a higher uptake during the Omicron wave through January, perhaps to 100M max by end of Jan. I'm reworking uptake relative to Omicron wave and tapering below pre-Omicron level from 2 weeks after the peak, allowing for 2nd dose pace from August/September and expecting 20% drop off. I now expect end of Jan: 86M, end Feb: 97M, end Mar: 106M... this isn't going to happen. Beyond this a new variant could still change things, but not by much unless vaccine efficacy was maintained. And from a social behaviour perspective, people will very likely be losing interest in taking any vaccines at all by May if they haven't already had them. Still keeping options open as recent Omicron-related questions have been unpredictable... I should allow a little more for any new booster mandating to come in, as they may well do during February, but Iâ€™m not convinced this will impact the outcome.

Omicron is running fast through populations if it starts subsiding significantly in a month, people will be less likely to see a booster. https://covid.cdc.gov/covid-data-tracker/#vaccinations_vacc-total-admin-rate-total

Using the first two dose paths as type curves, it seems extremely unlikely that boosters will cross 165M before April. Even a linear extrapolation puts the value crossing in late April. Given the drop off in uptake between doses 1 and 2, and the performance of boosters so far, there is a very strong argument that the value never crosses the target. I'll revisit the data in a week, just in case the holidays created anomalies. But right now, the S-curve is far below the other doses.

Current data, which may still be distorted by the holiday season, suggests 0.4-0.5m individuals are being boosted per day, down from 0.85 before Christmas. These ranges suggest the earliest date to hit the question target is in mid April (getting back to 0.85 per day), and that near the end of June is feasible as is not reaching the target until after the 1 July (whether the rate is 0.4m or 0.5m determines these buckets and I don't see how anyone could tell yet within such a narrow band when there are so many factors influencing the rate). Data in the next two weeks seems quite important to how this will resolve (do rates pick up again after the holidays, with rising cases and a push to get people protected, or will they stay at current levels or even fall as individuals decide they don't care and Omicron is not as serious an illness)?

Updating based on current CDC number, rerunning my forecasts using both 3 parameter Logistic and Gompertz functions. I then aggregate with selected peers. My impression is that the booster dosing is slowing down, similar to comments by @mwokasch and others. My 95% prediction intervals for both the Logistic and Gompertz curves do not reach 165M through Q3 of 2022 based on the data to date. However, I want to temper relying simply on the modeling alone - that's where I've been burned by "off spreadsheet risks" before. That's where I aggregate with other colleagues' thinking ( @belikewater, @cdob63, @Emking, @mwokasch,etc) knowing that each of us has a little different perspective and access to different ideas and insights. Anyway, will probably be betting more and more on Bin #5 unless something significant occurs to change the trend.

As of Jan 4th, 2022 there are 204M fully vaccinated individuals and 68.7M with a booster. [1] If you are unwilling to get the vaccine at this point, you are very unlikely to get the booster. A lot of people became vaccinated because of mandates and pressure. I think COVID-19 will peak in Jan-Feb and then fall off steeply. Pressure to get a booster will subside. Also, since Omicron will be more mild, people will be less inclined to get the booster. If there is a booster for Omicron, they will get that instead as we get farther along.

Not zero on bin 1 because a lot of booster mandates may have Feb 1 deadlines. Relatively high on bin 2 because more booster mandates may have deadlines in bin 2. Relatively lower on bin 3 because if mandates don't get boosters to 165M by bin 2, then it would probably happen by mid June at current rates. Relatively lower on bin 4 because if it doesn't happen by bin 3, then people are probably going to want to wait for an Omicron vaccine, even if Delta is still circulating at comparatively low levels, because they won't be thinking about next winter, and illness and death are becoming normalized. Highest on bin 5 because as Omicron vaccines likely start to become available in March, many people are probably going to want to get an Omicron vaccine instead.

3.932M added/week in the past 2 weeks. 68.701M on Dec 30. 91.299M to go to reach 160M. 91.299M/3.932M = 23.2 weeks => mid-June. By then, a lot of people will be waiting for Omicron shots, even if Delta is still circulating. Otoh, a lot of booster mandates are coming into play in February.

Also, in some countries there has been a push for letting the Omicron variant spread to induce natural immunity. It is possible that the number of vaccinated with booster doses never reaches the 165 million mark.

Detailed Methodology:
Americans are idiots.

The monthly rate of boosters has been around 25 million a month [1]. Projecting that out would put it at 3.9 months to 165 million, which would be near the end of April. But in the month prior to second doses reaching 165 million the rate was just 9 million doses in that month [2]. It took about 2 months to get that last 25 million. So if I just roughly guess we get to 140 million at a rate of 25 million a month, that puts it at just under 3 months to get there, and then add 2 months to get the last 25 million. 5 months from now would be end of May. I'm skewing toward later than that though because things could slow down more than that considering the booster rollout has set a slower pace than second doses.
At the 30% current level after almost 2 years I canâ€™t see 65% level late into 2022.
The Trumpists will continue to cause trouble

Started by modeling as a Logistic growth function seeing the temporal data for US vaccinations and boosters so far. Both 3-parameter Logistic and Gompertz functions fit the CDC data very well. I then used Sam Savage's SIP Math Tools to run several 000 monte-carlo trials using the Gompertz fit out through the year and collect statistics on the % of times the cumulative counts were greater than the 165M threshold. Finally, I aggregated with selected peers to arrive at the rough numbers above. So far the booster dosing appears to be slowing down. If there is a mandate to do this to be employed (etc), then I could see acceleration of the current pattern but if not, I think the effort may lose steam. Hopefully I'm wrong. I see that some other respected colleagues (@belikewater, @jleibowich, and @cdob63) also participating so I will be interested to see if they have a different view of things.
